<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-09-18T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-09-18T13:00:00-05:00" n="606" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d606">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">501.BB Palestine/9–1748: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Embassy in the United Kingdom</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                            </seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-09-18T14:00:00-04:00">September
                                    18, 1948—2 p. m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>3690. For Ambassador Douglas.</p>
                        <list>
                            <label>(1)</label>
                            <item>We agree (para 2 <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 4153,
                                Sept. 17) Bernadotte report may be published as early as Sept.
                                20.</item>
                            <label>(2)</label>
                            <item>Secretary will make decision in Paris (para 6). Confidentially our
                                present inclination is to make statement there before
                                British.</item>
                            <label>(3)</label>
                            <item>Sec plans leave Washington early afternoon Sept. 19, arriving in
                                Paris Sept. 20.</item>
                            <label>(4)</label>
                            <item>We are preparing US statement (para 8) which Sec will probably
                                take with him for discussion with <gloss target="#t_GADel1">GADel</gloss> Paris following arrival.</item>
                        </list>
                        <p>Sent London, repeated Paris for Jessup and McClintock in reply <gloss target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 59, Sept. 18.<note n="1" xml:id="d606fn1">Not printed; Mr. McClintock, in this message to
                                Messrs. Lovett and Rusk, recommended strongly that there be no
                                ten-day delay in publishing the Bernadotte report and concluded:
                                “Bernadotte’s death will give maximum weight to recommendations in
                                his report. I feel that if report is issued promptly, there will
                                still be sufficient time for diplomatic preparation, particularly
                                since British already contemplate swift action.”
                                (501.BB/9–1848)</note>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Marshall</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>